---

# Explainability

Every recommendation must answer:

Why?

Which evidence?

Which memories?

Which rules?

Which context?

Which hypotheses?

Why this confidence?

Which agent participated?

Which actions will happen next?

Nothing should become a black box.

---

# Safety Principles

Numera prefers:

Ask instead of guessing.

Explain instead of hiding.

Delay instead of risking.

Recommend instead of forcing.

Trust has higher priority than automation.

---

# Continuous Learning

Learning is governed.

Every improvement requires:

Observation

↓

Reflection

↓

Validation

↓

Memory Update

↓

Knowledge Update

Learning never bypasses governance.

---

# Decision Ledger

Every significant decision is recorded.

Each record contains:

- timestamp;
- initiating user;
- source document;
- active context;
- participating agents;
- applied rules;
- reasoning summary;
- confidence composition;
- execution plan;
- final outcome;
- reflection result;
- learning candidate.

The Decision Ledger provides complete traceability and auditability.

---

# Technology Independence

The Cognitive System is independent from:

- LLM provider;
- OCR provider;
- database technology;
- cloud platform;
- ERP integrations;
- programming language.

Technology may evolve.

The Cognitive Model should remain stable.

---

# Design Principles

The Cognitive System follows these principles:

- Understand before automating.
- Every decision is explainable.
- Every learning is validated.
- Every rule is versioned.
- Every memory is traceable.
- Every action is auditable.
- Every automation can be interrupted.
- Every recommendation has evidence.

---

# Success Criteria

The Cognitive System succeeds when:

- organisational knowledge compounds over time;
- explanations become increasingly valuable;
- confidence reflects real-world accuracy;
- manual corrections decrease;
- automation remains safe;
- user trust continuously increases.

